 reaches beyond the study of the organizations themselves to explore their complex collaborative ventures with municipal governments—efforts that offer citizens a measure of hope for meeting housing, health, education, and environmental needs through experimentation, contracting, extension, and self-provisioning. These studies of Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Peru, and Mexico aim to advance both democracy and development by concentrating on the local "capillaries" of society, where demands, supports, and information are exchanged to keep the political organism healthy. Ultimately, assert the authors, democratization and development, like effective poverty reduction and social problem solving, must be achieved at the local level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aCaccia Bava, Silvio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaravedo, Baltazar M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavarozzi, Marcelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohn, Amélia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEcheverri-Gent, Elisavinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernandes, Rubem Cesar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoveman, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinez Nogueira, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoguel, Julio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMullahy, Laura, econtributor.4ctb